0) Prerequisites (one-time)

Install Git: [git-scm.com] ‚Üí install, keep defaults.

Install VS Code: [code.visualstudio.com].

Tell Git who you are (once):

Open VS Code ‚Üí Terminal ‚Üí New Terminal and run:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"


Sign in to GitHub in VS Code (easy auth):

In VS Code, click the Accounts icon (top-right) ‚Üí Sign in to GitHub ‚Üí authorize in browser.

Optional (advanced): set up SSH keys and use the SSH remote. If you skip this, HTTPS with Git Credential Manager works fine.

1) Push a brand-new local project to GitHub

Goal: You have a folder on your computer that‚Äôs not yet on GitHub.

Open the folder in VS Code (File ‚Üí Open Folder).

Initialize Git:

Click the Source Control icon (branch symbol) on the left.

Click Initialize Repository.

Create a .gitignore (optional but recommended):

Add a file named .gitignore (e.g., for Node: node_modules/, for Python: __pycache__/).

Stage & commit your first snapshot:

In Source Control, hover each changed file ‚Üí + (stage), or click + next to Changes to stage all.

Enter a message like Initial commit ‚Üí press Ctrl/Cmd + Enter (or click the checkmark) to Commit.

Publish to GitHub:

In the Source Control view, click Publish Branch (or Publish to GitHub).

Choose Private or Public. VS Code creates the repo on GitHub and sets the remote.

Verify: You‚Äôll see a ‚ÄúSynchronize Changes‚Äù ‚Üï button in the bottom-left. Click it if prompted to push.

You‚Äôre now live on GitHub üéâ



Daily Flow in VS Code
1) Before leaving the office

Open Source Control panel

Left sidebar ‚Üí click the branch icon (Source Control).

Stage all your changes

Click the + button next to Changes (or hover each file and click +).

Commit

Type a message like Work in progress in the text box above the file list.

Press Ctrl + Enter (Windows) or Cmd + Enter (Mac)
(or click the ‚úì checkmark at the top).

Push to GitHub

At the bottom-left, click ‚Üï Sync Changes.

VS Code will push your commit to GitHub so the home computer can pull it.

2) At home (before starting work)

Pull the latest changes

Bottom-left ‚Üí click ‚Üï Sync Changes (this does a pull first, then push if needed).

If no changes to push yet, it will just pull.

Do your edits in VS Code.

Commit & push when done for the night

Stage ‚Üí Commit ‚Üí Sync Changes (same steps as office).

3) Next day back at the office

Sync before starting

Click ‚Üï Sync Changes ‚Äî this pulls last night‚Äôs work from GitHub.

Make your edits.

Commit & Sync Changes before leaving again.


First-time setup at home

Copy your GitHub repo link

Go to the repo on GitHub.

Click the green Code button.

Select HTTPS (unless you use SSH) and copy the link.
Example:

https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git


Open VS Code ‚Üí Clone the repo

In VS Code, press Ctrl + Shift + P (Windows) or Cmd + Shift + P (Mac) to open the Command Palette.

Type Git: Clone ‚Üí select it.

Paste the GitHub URL ‚Üí press Enter.

Choose a folder location

Pick where you want the code stored locally (e.g., Documents/Projects).

Open the project

VS Code will ask if you want to Open the cloned repo ‚Äî click Yes.

Install dependencies (if needed)

If it‚Äôs a Node, Python, or other project that needs packages, install them now (e.g., npm install, pip install -r requirements.txt, etc.).
